The '''hydrogen anion''', H<sup>−</sup>, is a [[Electric charge|negative]] [[ion]] of hydrogen, <!-- don’t link as [[hydrogen ion]], it’s a set index! -->that is, a [[hydrogen atom]] that has captured an extra electron. The hydrogen anion is an important constituent of the atmosphere of [[star]]s, such as the [[Sun]].  In chemistry, this ion is called '''[[hydride]]'''. The ion has [[Two-electron atom|two electrons]] bound by the [[electromagnetic force]] to a nucleus containing one proton.

The binding energy of H<sup>−</sup> equals the binding energy of an extra electron to a hydrogen atom, called [[electron affinity]] of hydrogen. It is measured to be {{val|0.754195|(19)|ul=eV}} or {{val|0.0277161|(62)|ul=hartree}} (see [[Electron affinity (data page)]]). The total ground state energy thus becomes {{val|-14.359888|u=eV}}.

==Occurrence==
The hydrogen anion is an important species in the photosphere of the Sun. It absorbs energies in the range 0.75–4.0 [[electronvolt|eV]], which ranges from the [[infrared]] into the [[visible spectrum]] ({{harvnb|Rau|1999}}, {{harvnb|Srinivasan|1999}}). It also occurs in the Earth's [[ionosphere]] ({{harvnb|Rau|1999}}), and can be produced in particle accelerators.

Its existence was first proven theoretically by [[Hans Bethe]] in 1929 ({{harvnb|Bethe|1929}}). H<sup>−</sup> is unusual because, in its free form, it has no [[bound state|bound]] [[energy level|excited states]], as was finally proven in 1977 ({{harvnb|Hill|1977}}). It has been studied experimentally using [[particle accelerator]]s ({{harvnb|Bryant|1977}}).

In chemistry, the [[hydride]] anion is hydrogen that has the formal [[oxidation state]] −1.

The term hydride is probably most often used to describe compounds of hydrogen with other elements in which the hydrogen is in the formal −1 [[oxidation state]].  In most such compounds the bonding between the hydrogen and its nearest neighbor is covalent. An example of a hydride is the [[borohydride]] anion ({{chem|BH|4|-}}).

